pt">tes patient and nursing interests on a wide range of issues by working closely with the Government, the UK parliaments and other national and European political institutions, trade unions, professional bodies and voluntary organisations.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The RCN welco</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mes the opportunity to submit evidence to the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Health Committee’s annual inquiry in to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">public expenditure in the NHS. The RCN has responded to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the elements of the terms of reference as</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> posed by the Committee which it feels qualified to comment on. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.0</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Exe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">cutive summary </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The RCN through its </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Frontline First </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">campaign has consistently raised the problem that NHS trusts are making short term cuts to workforce and services in order to save money. This situation has not changed. Since May 2010 the qualified nurs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing and midwifery workforce has been cut by 3,859 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">full </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">time equivalents or 6,468 headcount.  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Cuts are happening in the areas which most need investment – such as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in the community and in mental health services. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The RCN accepts that financial savings must be made, but too often trusts are not looking to the long term and making short term cuts. RCN members are growing frustrated that there is no sign of the reinvestment of any of the efficiency savings. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The RCN </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">supports better integration of services and nursing can play a prominent role in that. Too often, however, the integration of services is piece meal and driven by individual clinicians rather than system</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">wide design. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is the view of the RCN that fundin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">g allocations should be based on a combination of age and deprivation. Focussing on only one of these factors may disproportionately affect individuals and whole localities. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Inadequate social care provision is placing a huge strain on NHS services which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are increasingly being left to plug the gaps in local authority commissioned services. This </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is contributing to the pressures on Accident and Emergency departments</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the growing problem of the ‘revolving door’ of hospital readmissions. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.0</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Plans being m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ade by NHS bodies to enable them to meet the Nicholson Challenge, and whether the NHS is succeeding in making efficiency gains rather that cuts. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The RCN accepts that the NHS needs to make financial efficiency savings due to the current economic climate. However, in far too many cases, as we have highlighted in previous submissions to the Committee, NHS bodies are making short term cuts to services </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and personnel rather than well thought through, genuine efficiency savings. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These cuts will, and are, inevitably affecting the quality of patient care. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The RCN’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Frontline First </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">campaign collects and publishes data on cuts to NHS personnel and specif</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ically nursing posts. The campaign calls for our members on the ground to tell us where they are seeing cuts to posts, where waste is eviden</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and where innovations are developed. This information is the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> robustly verified and analysed before it is publishe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d. More recently the campaign has developed to use the Government’s own workforce figures. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">According to the most recent data (for July 2013), the qualified nursing, midwifery and health visiting workforce lost 3,859 FTE roles (6,468 headcount) since </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">May 2010, a decrease of 1.2 per cent.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Support to doctors and nursing staff, including roles such as health care assistants and assistant practitioners, has also decreased by a similar proportion, with 2,719 full time posts lost (7,058 headcount).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.4</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Alt</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hough the aggregated qualified nursing, midwifery and health visiting workforce has decreased over the last three years, the picture is more complex than this. Workforce numbers for both qualified midwives and qualified health visitors have actually increa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sed. The midwifery workforce has increased by 1,311 FTE roles since May 2010, and the health visiting workforce has increased by 700 FTE roles.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> These figures, however, blur the effect of cuts to the nursing workforce.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> If these figures are removed from the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">aggregated data, it indicates a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">true fall of 5,870 FTE nurse roles (or 7,578 headcount) since May 2010</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.5</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Although the nursing workforce has decreased overall, posts have been lost from different services at varying rates. The RCN is extremely concerne</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d that the areas which have seen the greatest proportional workforce losses are also those where investment is urgently needed.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In mental health services, the workforce has seen a decrease of nearly 2,000 full time nursing staff since 2010.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This is de</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">spite years of rising demand for mental health care. In England, 48,631 people were detained in hospital for assessment and/or treatment of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mental disorder under the Mental Health Act in 2011/2012, and a further 4,220 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">patients were subject to community t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reatment orders (CTOs) – a 5</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> per cent</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> increase in detentions and 10</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> per cent</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> increase in CTOs compared to the previous year. Mental health services are now showing increasing levels of strain, with evidence suggesting </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">at least 1,711 mental health beds</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (9 per</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cent of the total) were closed between April 2011 and August 2013.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The learning disability nursing workforce has also seen significant long term decline, with 800 full time roles lost since 2010, a fall of around 15 per cent.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.7</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">After a decade of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> workforce expansion, peaking in 2009-2010,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">community</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> nursing workforce has in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the last three years seen a fall of 1,744 full time roles, or 3.6 per cent of the workforce.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Despite rhetoric of a shift from acute to community models of care, the proporti</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">on of nurses working in community services has changed very little, from 14.3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> per cent</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of the total nursing workforce in 2002, to 15.1 per cent in 2012.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Losses have been particularly acute in the district nursing workforce, which has been declining year on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> year for the last decade, with 1,312 full time posts lost since 2010 (a 17 per cent decrease).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.8</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In addition to those posts lost so far, the RCN’s 2012 report on the community nursing workforce identified that services would suffer disproportionately </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">more from an ag</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing nursing workforce.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In the community workforce, 38 per cent of nurses were found to be aged 50 and over, compared to 23.6 per cent of the acute, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">older people</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and general nursing workforce.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">With 59.2 per cent of the community nursing work</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">force aged 45 and over, a large proportion will reach </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">retirement age</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the next decade</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, compounding the urgent need to build the community w</span><a name="_ftnref1"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">orkforce capacity in the future</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.9</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The RCN is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">aware</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, through intelligence and information gathered,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of many NHS trusts which have instigated recruitment freezes and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">delete </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">vacancies so that they can reduce their wage bill through </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">natural wastage</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’ and avoid making direct job cuts</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> This obviously has a negative effect on the level of service that can be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">provided. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.10</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Nursing posts are also being downbanded, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">where nursing staff are having to accept the reg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ra</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ding of their jobs. It is also where </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">experienced qualified nursing posts </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are replaced </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with those of a lower band or unregistered health care assista</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nts. The RCN has repeatedly drawn attention to these issues and the risk to patient safety they represent. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.11</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Nurse staffing levels and skill mix have a direct impact on the health outcomes that can be achieved. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Government should mandate the use of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> staffing levels tools</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> which allow for local flexibility and variability</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. In too many cases we are seeing patients suffer because of inadequate nurse staffing levels. In </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">several</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> recent </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Government commissioned reports this correlation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">between nurse staffing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> levels and patient outcomes has been </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">identified; most recently by Sir Bruce Keogh in his review of 14 NHS trust with above average outliers in mortality rates</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. These trusts were put under ‘special measures’ with all of them undertaking urgent reviews of t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">heir nurse staffing levels. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is clear that these strains have been brought about by financial constraint. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Staffing levels and skill mix must be planned and based on a sound clinical rationale, not budget availability.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.12</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is now an overwhelming e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">vidence base for the use of mandatory safe staffing levels; it is now time to act on this evidence. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.0</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Effectiveness of the mechanisms by which resources are distributed geographically in the NHS.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">NHS England is currently reviewing the funding </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">allocation formula that is used to allocate funds to CCGs across England</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.The proposed revisions to the allocation formula mean that there will be no weighting for levels of deprivation in local areas, or which have poor health outcomes. Instead, the new a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">llocation formula will be based on the predicted demand for health</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">care for the population as a whole. Some of the biggest losers in terms of NHS funding cover the same areas of the country where we have the highest incidences of chronic and long-term illn</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ess.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Research published by the HSJ and the University of Liverpool on 7th October 2013 shows that, under the new proposed formula</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">those </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">areas of the country </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that stand to lose the most in per capita health funding are also the same areas that alre</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ady have the highest lev</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">els of preventable early deaths</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hose areas</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> where people with long-term health conditions have the lowest quality of life will also lose the mo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">st in per capita health funding</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">areas </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">whose councils have had the largest budget cu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ts imposed from central government are the same areas that will lose the most in per capita health funding</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The RCN is committed to reducing inequalities in access to health care. The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">RCN</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> believes that the funding allocation should continue to have a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mixed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">system of weighting to reflect levels of deprivation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and also the age of populations </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in local areas, or which have poor health outcomes.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.0</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Prospects for the long-term viability of NHS trusts and NHS foundation trusts. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5.1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The NHS continues t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">o face one of the most significant financial challenges in its history. The anticipated continuation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and increase </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of costs saving measures within the NHS beyond 2014/15 will inevitably result in even further pressures on the delivery of services. The RCN h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as consistently highlighted that current funding is unlikely to meet the costs of the rising health demand.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5.2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Despite the stated intentions of politicians, health experts and NHS mangers to move services from acute hospitals into the community, both to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reduce costs and to have more person-centred care, the RCN on the whole has found very little clear evidence of this shift actually happening on the ground. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Moving care away from secondary settings in to the community must be seen as key to achieving meani</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ngful efficiencies and service redesign. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5.3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The RCN believes that NHS organisations need to work together to provide real service transformation that brings care closer to home and integrates care around the patient. This can result in efficiency savings and benefit patients, but will require co-ope</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ration between trusts and investment in the short-term. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6.0</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The impact on the provision of adult social care of the 2010 spending review settlement and the ability of local authorities to make the necessary efficiency savings</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The King’s Fund reports</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that l</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ocal authority spending on social care has fallen for four years in succession, and fewer people are using publicly funded care than ever before. With 87 per cent of local authorities setting their eligibility criteria at substantial or higher, it h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as become much harder for people </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to access care</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">educing the spending on social care  will inevitably </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">lead to an increase in need and also the further complication of individuals requiring care. The NHS and nursing staff, both in acute and communit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y settings, are then required to fill the growing gaps in social care provision for patients with increasingly complex conditions.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 75</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> per cent</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of RCN members responding to a 2012 survey on community nursing said that the pressure on their team had increase</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d as a result of cuts to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> social care provision made by l</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">oca</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">uthorities.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Readmissions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> or the so-called ‘revolving door’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are a result of insufficient support in social care or community settings. Nursing staff</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> frequently</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> experience the frustratio</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n of seeing a healthy patient discharged into community care, only to see them </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">readmitted into acute setting</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> weeks down the line owing to the absence of appropriate community care.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.4</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Care Quality Commission’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The state of health and adult social </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">care in England: an overview of key themes in care in 2011/12</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> found that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">if discharge arrangements and planning for discharge are not sufficient, there is an increased risk of emergency readmission,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the national average for emergency readmissions within 0-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">7 days of discharge that required at least an overnight stay was 2.5 per cent, but this increased to  3.8 per cent</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for emergency readmissions within 8-30 days, where external factors were more likely to contribute to the readmission.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.5</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A recent report </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">from the Nuffield Trust and Health Foundation illustrated what we are hearing from our members. It showed that the number of elderly patients who have been readmitted following early discharge has risen from 3,658 in 2001/2 to 6,810 in 2010/11, a rise of 6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">9 per cent. The report also showed that the situation had worsened in the last three years</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Delayed discharge figures can be used to quantify the levels of pick up by the NHS of social care needs.  On any one day a significant number of patients (ap</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">prox</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">imately</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 4,000 in England), mostly over the age of 75, are being cared for on an acute ward in hospital when they could be cared for in the community.  In 60</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> per cent</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of these </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cases it is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> caused by social services failing to meet their responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> they are either not assessing the patient for community care or cannot provide the care the patient needs to be able to leave the acute care setting</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7.0</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The impact on NHS plans of decisions currently being made by local authorities and the use of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">additional funding for social care being made available through the NHS budget</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">7.1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The additional funding taken from the NHS budget - £1 billion a year by 2014 - is intended to be used for partnership working between the NHS and social care</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> providers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">allow for more people to be cared for in the community.  However, this funding is not ring-fenced and the RCN is concerned that this money is not being spent directly on this. The King’s Fund</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> shares this concern</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and reports that t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he transfer of NHS resourc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">es is helping, but not always in the way intended – </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">provid</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> additional capacity for care. Of the money allocated from the NHS to promote joint </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">working this year, 32 per cent (£253 million) is being used to offset cuts </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> loca</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> authority </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">services and to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">help meet demographic pressures.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">7.2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Using the NHS budget to bail out social care goes against the Government's pledge to ring-fence and protect NHS spending. Without ensuring that these funds are spent on providing social care services, the NHS is still</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> faced with filling the gaps in social care provision with all its associated costs and problems described above</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> but with £1 billion less funding.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8.0</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Progress on making efficiencies through the integration of health and social care services</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">8.1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Integra</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tion of health and social care services is not only seen as providing patients with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> timely access to seamless care, but also a way of eliminating costly duplication of services and ensuring patients are given the care </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">they need in the right setting.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Howeve</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">r, integration of health and social care services in England is still very much piece meal an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d individually programme based.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">8.2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">While there are many excellent examples of integrated care delivery across the country, including specific teams, projects an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d processes, many of which are led or designed by nurses, there is a wide variation.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Some examples have been enabled by the development of NHS Care Trusts, integrated or pooled budgets, and the Department of Health’s Health and Social Care Integration Pro</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">gramme (HSCIP)</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. However, there have been inconsistencies in policy and project implementation with no significant learning mechanisms in place or application of best practice.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> We hope that the Government programme of integration ‘Pioneers’ is successful i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n developing a tangible way forward in this area. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">8.3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Funding issues also impact on the ability to integrate services, as RCN members are increasingly informing us, multi-disciplinary teams are being left short of critical impact from social workers and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">other disciplines owing to budgetary cuts.  This means that patients with complex needs are not benefiting from crucial multi-disciplinary </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">services</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, which look at their needs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> holistically</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and aim to ensure that their patient journey is smooth.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">     </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">8.4</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">espite the notable effort of nursing and other care professionals, the structures, processes and systems in place have not consistently been designed around the service </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">user to allow integrated care. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If integrated care is to become a system-wide reality, t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hen consistent political</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> focus and leadership at local </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and national levels are needed to ensure appropriate mechanisms, including funding,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are in place</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">enable </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the delivery of joined up care at all levels</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">RCN (2012) The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">community nursing workforce in England. Available at:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><a href="https://rcnmail.rcn.org.uk/owa/redir.aspx?C=iyyUPHjuDkmuFFX4KenubNIbheNUrNAI6NOFaIKuEPLsJkNiz92Cf3XWhfOI8wfDG3pqExrNC64.&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.nursingtimes.net%2fJournals%2f2012%2f05%2f11%2fu%2fq%2fb%2fThe-Community-Nursing-Workforce-in-England.pdf" target="_blank"><span style="color:#800080; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.nursingtimes.net/Journals/2012/05/11/u/q/b/The-Community-Nursing-Workforce-in-England.pdf</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> http://www.hsj.co.uk/news/finance/redistributing-ccg-funding-could-mean-real-te</span><span style="font-family:'Ti